On August 5, 2012, the President of the United States received a briefing on a shooting that took place in Oak Creek, Wisconsin. He then made calls to various officials including FBI Director Bob Mueller, Chief of Staff Jack Lew, and Homeland Security Advisor John Brennan to receive updates on the situation. The President also called Wisconsin Governor Scott Walker, Oak Creek Mayor Steve Scaffidi, and trustee of the Sikh Temple Charanjeet Singh to express his condolences for the lives lost and his concern for the injured. The President was informed that the situation at the Sikh Temple was under control and that the lone gunman had been killed by a police officer. He was also updated on the condition of some of the victims and directed the federal government to assist in the investigation. The President emphasized the importance of denouncing the violence and highlighted the contributions of the Sikh community to the American family.